{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_32d46cd203514d638a96ddd3","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t<img src=\"docs/imgs/acme.png\" width=\"50%\">\n2\t\n3\t# Acme: a research framework for reinforcement learning\n4\t\n5\t[![PyPI Python Version][pypi-versions-badge]][pypi]\n6\t[![PyPI version][pypi-badge]][pypi]\n7\t[![acme-tests][tests-badge]][tests]\n8\t[![Documentation Status][rtd-badge]][documentation]\n9\t\n10\t[pypi-versions-badge]: https://img.shields.io/pypi/pyversions/dm-acme\n11\t[pypi-badge]: https://badge.fury.io/py/dm-acme.svg\n12\t[pypi]: https://pypi.org/project/dm-acme/\n13\t[tests-badge]: https://github.com/deepmind/acme/workflows/acme-tests/badge.svg\n14\t[tests]: https://github.com/deepmind/acme/actions/workflows/ci.yml\n15\t[rtd-badge]: https://readthedocs.org/projects/dm-acme/badge/?version=latest\n16\t\n17\tAcme is a library of reinforcement learning (RL) building blocks that strives to\n18\texpose simple, efficient, and readable agents. These agents first and foremost\n19\tserve both as reference implementations as well as providing strong baselines\n20\tfor algorithm performance. However, the baseline agents exposed by Acme should\n21\talso provide enough flexibility and simplicity that they can be used as a\n22\tstarting block for novel research. Finally, the building blocks of Acme are\n23\tdesigned in such a way that the agents can be run at multiple scales (e.g.\n24\tsingle-stream vs. distributed agents).\n25\t\n26\t## Getting started\n27\t\n28\tThe quickest way to get started is to take a look at the detailed working code\n29\texamples found in the [examples] subdirectory. These show how to instantiate a\n30\tnumber of different agents and run them within a variety of environments. See\n31\tthe [quickstart notebook][Quickstart] for an even quicker dive into using a\n32\tsingle agent. Even more detail on the internal construction of an agent can be\n33\tfound inside our [tutorial notebook][Tutorial]. Finally, a full description Acme\n34\tand its underlying components can be found by referring to the [documentation].\n35\tMore background information and details behind the design decisions can be found\n36\tin our [technical report][Paper].\n37\t\n38\t> NOTE: Acme is first and foremost a framework for RL research written by\n39\t> researchers, for researchers. We use it for our own work on a daily basis. So\n40\t> with that in mind, while we will make every attempt to keep everything in good\n41\t> working order, things may break occasionally. But if so we will make our best\n42\t> effort to fix them as quickly as possible!\n43\t\n44\t[examples]: examples/\n45\t[tutorial]: https://colab.research.google.com/github/deepmind/acme/blob/master/examples/tutorial.ipynb\n46\t[quickstart]: https://colab.research.google.com/github/deepmind/acme/blob/master/examples/quickstart.ipynb\n47\t[documentation]: https://dm-acme.readthedocs.io/\n48\t[paper]: https://arxiv.org/abs/2006.00979\n49\t\n50\t## Installation\n51\t\n52\tTo get up and running quickly just follow the steps below:\n53\t\n54\t1.  While you can install Acme in your standard python environment, we\n55\t    *strongly* recommend using a\n56\t    [Python virtual environment](https://docs.python.org/3/tutorial/venv.html)\n57\t    to manage your dependencies. This should help to avoid version conflicts and\n58\t    just generally make the installation process easier.\n59\t\n60\t    ```bash\n61\t    python3 -m venv acme\n62\t    source acme/bin/activate\n63\t    pip install --upgrade pip setuptools wheel\n64\t    ```\n65\t\n66\t1.  While the core `dm-acme` library can be pip installed directly, the set of\n67\t    dependencies included for installation is minimal. In particular, to run any\n68\t    of the included agents you will also need either [JAX] or [TensorFlow]\n69\t    depending on the agent. As a result we recommend installing these components\n70\t    as well, i.e.\n71\t\n72\t    ```bash\n73\t    pip install dm-acme[jax,tf]\n74\t    ```\n75\t\n76\t1.  Finally, to install a few example environments (including [gym],\n77\t    [dm_control], and [bsuite]):\n78\t\n79\t    ```bash\n80\t    pip install dm-acme[envs]\n81\t    ```\n82\t\n83\t1.  **Installing from github**: if you're interested in running the\n84\t    bleeding-edge version of Acme, you can do so by cloning the Acme GitHub\n85\t    repository and then executing following command from the main directory\n86\t    (where `setup.py` is located):\n87\t\n88\t    ```bash\n89\t    pip install .[jax,tf,testing,envs]\n90\t    ```\n91\t\n92\t## Citing Acme\n93\t\n94\tIf you use Acme in your work, please cite the updated accompanying\n95\t[technical report][paper]:\n96\t\n97\t```bibtex\n98\t@article{hoffman2020acme,\n99\t    title={Acme: A Research Framework for Distributed Reinforcement Learning},\n100\t    author={\n101\t        Matthew W. Hoffman and Bobak Shahriari and John Aslanides and\n102\t        Gabriel Barth-Maron and Nikola Momchev and Danila Sinopalnikov and\n103\t        Piotr Sta\\'nczyk and Sabela Ramos and Anton Raichuk and\n104\t        Damien Vincent and L\\'eonard Hussenot and Robert Dadashi and\n105\t        Gabriel Dulac-Arnold and Manu Orsini and Alexis Jacq and\n106\t        Johan Ferret and Nino Vieillard and Seyed Kamyar Seyed Ghasemipour and\n107\t        Sertan Girgin and Olivier Pietquin and Feryal Behbahani and\n108\t        Tamara Norman and Abbas Abdolmaleki and Albin Cassirer and\n109\t        Fan Yang and Kate Baumli and Sarah Henderson and Abe Friesen and\n110\t        Ruba Haroun and Alex Novikov and Sergio G\\'omez Colmenarejo and\n111\t        Serkan Cabi and Caglar Gulcehre and Tom Le Paine and\n112\t        Srivatsan Srinivasan and Andrew Cowie and Ziyu Wang and Bilal Piot and\n113\t        Nando de Freitas\n114\t    },\n115\t    year={2020},\n116\t    journal={arXiv preprint arXiv:2006.00979},\n117\t    url={https://arxiv.org/abs/2006.00979},\n118\t}\n119\t```\n120\t\n121\t[JAX]: https://github.com/google/jax\n122\t[TensorFlow]: https://tensorflow.org\n123\t[gym]: https://github.com/openai/gym\n124\t[dm_control]: https://github.com/deepmind/dm_env\n125\t[dm_env]: https://github.com/deepmind/dm_env\n126\t[bsuite]: https://github.com/deepmind/bsuite\n127\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"db66edc6-7466-48f8-a0c7-bcc0b007df7f","uuid":"c068edec-7e06-45db-a3c1-1d75a1fb2535","timestamp":"2026-04-06T16:59:17.730Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/README.md","content":"<img src=\"docs/imgs/acme.png\" width=\"50%\">\n\n# Acme: a research framework for reinforcement learning\n\n[![PyPI Python Version][pypi-versions-badge]][pypi]\n[![PyPI version][pypi-badge]][pypi]\n[![acme-tests][tests-badge]][tests]\n[![Documentation Status][rtd-badge]][documentation]\n\n[pypi-versions-badge]: https://img.shields.io/pypi/pyversions/dm-acme\n[pypi-badge]: https://badge.fury.io/py/dm-acme.svg\n[pypi]: https://pypi.org/project/dm-acme/\n[tests-badge]: https://github.com/deepmind/acme/workflows/acme-tests/badge.svg\n[tests]: https://github.com/deepmind/acme/actions/workflows/ci.yml\n[rtd-badge]: https://readthedocs.org/projects/dm-acme/badge/?version=latest\n\nAcme is a library of reinforcement learning (RL) building blocks that strives to\nexpose simple, efficient, and readable agents. These agents first and foremost\nserve both as reference implementations as well as providing strong baselines\nfor algorithm performance. However, the baseline agents exposed by Acme should\nalso provide enough flexibility and simplicity that they can be used as a\nstarting block for novel research. Finally, the building blocks of Acme are\ndesigned in such a way that the agents can be run at multiple scales (e.g.\nsingle-stream vs. distributed agents).\n\n## Getting started\n\nThe quickest way to get started is to take a look at the detailed working code\nexamples found in the [examples] subdirectory. These show how to instantiate a\nnumber of different agents and run them within a variety of environments. See\nthe [quickstart notebook][Quickstart] for an even quicker dive into using a\nsingle agent. Even more detail on the internal construction of an agent can be\nfound inside our [tutorial notebook][Tutorial]. Finally, a full description Acme\nand its underlying components can be found by referring to the [documentation].\nMore background information and details behind the design decisions can be found\nin our [technical report][Paper].\n\n> NOTE: Acme is first and foremost a framework for RL research written by\n> researchers, for researchers. We use it for our own work on a daily basis. So\n> with that in mind, while we will make every attempt to keep everything in good\n> working order, things may break occasionally. But if so we will make our best\n> effort to fix them as quickly as possible!\n\n[examples]: examples/\n[tutorial]: https://colab.research.google.com/github/deepmind/acme/blob/master/examples/tutorial.ipynb\n[quickstart]: https://colab.research.google.com/github/deepmind/acme/blob/master/examples/quickstart.ipynb\n[documentation]: https://dm-acme.readthedocs.io/\n[paper]: https://arxiv.org/abs/2006.00979\n\n## Installation\n\nTo get up and running quickly just follow the steps below:\n\n1.  While you can install Acme in your standard python environment, we\n    *strongly* recommend using a\n    [Python virtual environment](https://docs.python.org/3/tutorial/venv.html)\n    to manage your dependencies. This should help to avoid version conflicts and\n    just generally make the installation process easier.\n\n    ```bash\n    python3 -m venv acme\n    source acme/bin/activate\n    pip install --upgrade pip setuptools wheel\n    ```\n\n1.  While the core `dm-acme` library can be pip installed directly, the set of\n    dependencies included for installation is minimal. In particular, to run any\n    of the included agents you will also need either [JAX] or [TensorFlow]\n    depending on the agent. As a result we recommend installing these components\n    as well, i.e.\n\n    ```bash\n    pip install dm-acme[jax,tf]\n    ```\n\n1.  Finally, to install a few example environments (including [gym],\n    [dm_control], and [bsuite]):\n\n    ```bash\n    pip install dm-acme[envs]\n    ```\n\n1.  **Installing from github**: if you're interested in running the\n    bleeding-edge version of Acme, you can do so by cloning the Acme GitHub\n    repository and then executing following command from the main directory\n    (where `setup.py` is located):\n\n    ```bash\n    pip install .[jax,tf,testing,envs]\n    ```\n\n## Citing Acme\n\nIf you use Acme in your work, please cite the updated accompanying\n[technical report][paper]:\n\n```bibtex\n@article{hoffman2020acme,\n    title={Acme: A Research Framework for Distributed Reinforcement Learning},\n    author={\n        Matthew W. Hoffman and Bobak Shahriari and John Aslanides and\n        Gabriel Barth-Maron and Nikola Momchev and Danila Sinopalnikov and\n        Piotr Sta\\'nczyk and Sabela Ramos and Anton Raichuk and\n        Damien Vincent and L\\'eonard Hussenot and Robert Dadashi and\n        Gabriel Dulac-Arnold and Manu Orsini and Alexis Jacq and\n        Johan Ferret and Nino Vieillard and Seyed Kamyar Seyed Ghasemipour and\n        Sertan Girgin and Olivier Pietquin and Feryal Behbahani and\n        Tamara Norman and Abbas Abdolmaleki and Albin Cassirer and\n        Fan Yang and Kate Baumli and Sarah Henderson and Abe Friesen and\n        Ruba Haroun and Alex Novikov and Sergio G\\'omez Colmenarejo and\n        Serkan Cabi and Caglar Gulcehre and Tom Le Paine and\n        Srivatsan Srinivasan and Andrew Cowie and Ziyu Wang and Bilal Piot and\n        Nando de Freitas\n    },\n    year={2020},\n    journal={arXiv preprint arXiv:2006.00979},\n    url={https://arxiv.org/abs/2006.00979},\n}\n```\n\n[JAX]: https://github.com/google/jax\n[TensorFlow]: https://tensorflow.org\n[gym]: https://github.com/openai/gym\n[dm_control]: https://github.com/deepmind/dm_env\n[dm_env]: https://github.com/deepmind/dm_env\n[bsuite]: https://github.com/deepmind/bsuite\n","numLines":127,"startLine":1,"totalLines":127}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_4c7562b8607845fcb2ad08c8","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Copyright 2018 DeepMind Technologies Limited. All rights reserved.\n2\t#\n3\t# Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the \"License\");\n4\t# you may not use this file except in compliance with the License.\n5\t# You may obtain a copy of the License at\n6\t#\n7\t#     http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0\n8\t#\n9\t# Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software\n10\t# distributed under the License is distributed on an \"AS IS\" BASIS,\n11\t# WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.\n12\t# See the License for the specific language governing permissions and\n13\t# limitations under the License.\n14\t\n15\t\"\"\"Install script for setuptools.\"\"\"\n16\t\n17\timport datetime\n18\tfrom importlib import util as import_util\n19\timport os\n20\timport sys\n21\t\n22\tfrom setuptools import find_packages\n23\tfrom setuptools import setup\n24\timport setuptools.command.build_py\n25\timport setuptools.command.develop\n26\t\n27\tspec = import_util.spec_from_file_location('_metadata', 'acme/_metadata.py')\n28\t_metadata = import_util.module_from_spec(spec)\n29\tspec.loader.exec_module(_metadata)\n30\t\n31\t# TODO(b/184148890): Add a release flag\n32\t\n33\t\n34\t# Any particular version of reverb needs to be pinned against a particular\n35\t# version of TF due to how it is built. While the versions below should be the\n36\t# most recent stable versions of each library we'll be explicit just make make\n37\t# sure this constraint is upheld.\n38\t\n39\ttensorflow = [\n40\t    'tensorflow==2.8.0',\n41\t    'tensorflow_probability==0.15.0',\n42\t    'tensorflow_datasets==4.6.0',\n43\t    'dm-reverb==0.7.2',\n44\t    'dm-launchpad==0.5.2',\n45\t]\n46\t\n47\tcore_requirements = [\n48\t    'absl-py',\n49\t    'dm-env',\n50\t    'dm-tree',\n51\t    'numpy',\n52\t    'pillow',\n53\t    'typing-extensions',\n54\t]\n55\t\n56\tjax_requirements = [\n57\t    'jax==0.4.3',\n58\t    'jaxlib==0.4.3',\n59\t    'chex',\n60\t    'dm-haiku',\n61\t    'flax',\n62\t    'optax',\n63\t    'rlax',\n64\t] + tensorflow\n65\t\n66\ttf_requirements = [\n67\t    'dm-sonnet',\n68\t    'trfl',\n69\t] + tensorflow\n70\t\n71\ttesting_requirements = [\n72\t    'pytype==2021.8.11',  # TODO(b/206926677): update to new version.\n73\t    'pytest-xdist',\n74\t]\n75\t\n76\tenvs_requirements = [\n77\t    'atari-py',\n78\t    'bsuite',\n79\t    'dm-control',\n80\t    'gym==0.25.0',\n81\t    'gym[atari]',\n82\t    'pygame==2.1.0',\n83\t    'rlds',\n84\t]\n85\t\n86\t\n87\tdef generate_requirements_file(path=None):\n88\t  \"\"\"Generates requirements.txt file with the Acme's dependencies.\n89\t\n90\t  It is used by Launchpad GCP runtime to generate Acme requirements to be\n91\t  installed inside the docker image. Acme itself is not installed from pypi,\n92\t  but instead sources are copied over to reflect any local changes made to\n93\t  the codebase.\n94\t\n95\t  Args:\n96\t    path: path to the requirements.txt file to generate.\n97\t  \"\"\"\n98\t  if not path:\n99\t    path = os.path.join(os.path.dirname(__file__), 'acme/requirements.txt')\n100\t  with open(path, 'w') as f:\n101\t    for package in set(core_requirements + jax_requirements + tf_requirements +\n102\t                       envs_requirements):\n103\t      f.write(f'{package}\\n')\n104\t\n105\t\n106\tlong_description = \"\"\"Acme is a library of reinforcement learning (RL) agents\n107\tand agent building blocks. Acme strives to expose simple, efficient,\n108\tand readable agents, that serve both as reference implementations of popular\n109\talgorithms and as strong baselines, while still providing enough flexibility\n110\tto do novel research. The design of Acme also attempts to provide multiple\n111\tpoints of entry to the RL problem at differing levels of complexity.\n112\t\n113\tFor more information see [github repository](https://github.com/deepmind/acme).\"\"\"\n114\t\n115\t# Get the version from metadata.\n116\tversion = _metadata.__version__\n117\t\n118\t# If we're releasing a nightly/dev version append to the version string.\n119\tif '--nightly' in sys.argv:\n120\t  sys.argv.remove('--nightly')\n121\t  version += '.dev' + datetime.datetime.now().strftime('%Y%m%d')\n122\t\n123\t\n124\tclass BuildPy(setuptools.command.build_py.build_py):\n125\t\n126\t  def run(self):\n127\t    generate_requirements_file()\n128\t    setuptools.command.build_py.build_py.run(self)\n129\t\n130\t\n131\tclass Develop(setuptools.command.develop.develop):\n132\t\n133\t  def run(self):\n134\t    generate_requirements_file()\n135\t    setuptools.command.develop.develop.run(self)\n136\t\n137\tcmdclass = {\n138\t    'build_py': BuildPy,\n139\t    'develop': Develop,\n140\t}\n141\t\n142\tsetup(\n143\t    name='dm-acme',\n144\t    version=version,\n145\t    cmdclass=cmdclass,\n146\t    description='A Python library for Reinforcement Learning.',\n147\t    long_description=long_description,\n148\t    long_description_content_type='text/markdown',\n149\t    author='DeepMind',\n150\t    license='Apache License, Version 2.0',\n151\t    keywords='reinforcement-learning python machine learning',\n152\t    packages=find_packages(),\n153\t    package_data={'': ['requirements.txt']},\n154\t    include_package_data=True,\n155\t    install_requires=core_requirements,\n156\t    extras_require={\n157\t        'jax': jax_requirements,\n158\t        'tf': tf_requirements,\n159\t        'testing': testing_requirements,\n160\t        'envs': envs_requirements,\n161\t    },\n162\t    classifiers=[\n163\t        'Development Status :: 3 - Alpha',\n164\t        'Environment :: Console',\n165\t        'Intended Audience :: Science/Research',\n166\t        'License :: OSI Approved :: Apache Software License',\n167\t        'Operating System :: POSIX :: Linux',\n168\t        'Programming Language :: Python :: 3',\n169\t        'Programming Language :: Python :: 3.8',\n170\t        'Programming Language :: Python :: 3.9',\n171\t        'Topic :: Scientific/Engineering :: Artificial Intelligence',\n172\t    ],\n173\t)\n174\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"db66edc6-7466-48f8-a0c7-bcc0b007df7f","uuid":"bc695c53-40d3-4554-b54a-e16170d2a299","timestamp":"2026-04-06T16:59:17.733Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/setup.py","content":"# Copyright 2018 DeepMind Technologies Limited. All rights reserved.\n#\n# Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the \"License\");\n# you may not use this file except in compliance with the License.\n# You may obtain a copy of the License at\n#\n#     http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0\n#\n# Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software\n# distributed under the License is distributed on an \"AS IS\" BASIS,\n# WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.\n# See the License for the specific language governing permissions and\n# limitations under the License.\n\n\"\"\"Install script for setuptools.\"\"\"\n\nimport datetime\nfrom importlib import util as import_util\nimport os\nimport sys\n\nfrom setuptools import find_packages\nfrom setuptools import setup\nimport setuptools.command.build_py\nimport setuptools.command.develop\n\nspec = import_util.spec_from_file_location('_metadata', 'acme/_metadata.py')\n_metadata = import_util.module_from_spec(spec)\nspec.loader.exec_module(_metadata)\n\n# TODO(b/184148890): Add a release flag\n\n\n# Any particular version of reverb needs to be pinned against a particular\n# version of TF due to how it is built. While the versions below should be the\n# most recent stable versions of each library we'll be explicit just make make\n# sure this constraint is upheld.\n\ntensorflow = [\n    'tensorflow==2.8.0',\n    'tensorflow_probability==0.15.0',\n    'tensorflow_datasets==4.6.0',\n    'dm-reverb==0.7.2',\n    'dm-launchpad==0.5.2',\n]\n\ncore_requirements = [\n    'absl-py',\n    'dm-env',\n    'dm-tree',\n    'numpy',\n    'pillow',\n    'typing-extensions',\n]\n\njax_requirements = [\n    'jax==0.4.3',\n    'jaxlib==0.4.3',\n    'chex',\n    'dm-haiku',\n    'flax',\n    'optax',\n    'rlax',\n] + tensorflow\n\ntf_requirements = [\n    'dm-sonnet',\n    'trfl',\n] + tensorflow\n\ntesting_requirements = [\n    'pytype==2021.8.11',  # TODO(b/206926677): update to new version.\n    'pytest-xdist',\n]\n\nenvs_requirements = [\n    'atari-py',\n    'bsuite',\n    'dm-control',\n    'gym==0.25.0',\n    'gym[atari]',\n    'pygame==2.1.0',\n    'rlds',\n]\n\n\ndef generate_requirements_file(path=None):\n  \"\"\"Generates requirements.txt file with the Acme's dependencies.\n\n  It is used by Launchpad GCP runtime to generate Acme requirements to be\n  installed inside the docker image. Acme itself is not installed from pypi,\n  but instead sources are copied over to reflect any local changes made to\n  the codebase.\n\n  Args:\n    path: path to the requirements.txt file to generate.\n  \"\"\"\n  if not path:\n    path = os.path.join(os.path.dirname(__file__), 'acme/requirements.txt')\n  with open(path, 'w') as f:\n    for package in set(core_requirements + jax_requirements + tf_requirements +\n                       envs_requirements):\n      f.write(f'{package}\\n')\n\n\nlong_description = \"\"\"Acme is a library of reinforcement learning (RL) agents\nand agent building blocks. Acme strives to expose simple, efficient,\nand readable agents, that serve both as reference implementations of popular\nalgorithms and as strong baselines, while still providing enough flexibility\nto do novel research. The design of Acme also attempts to provide multiple\npoints of entry to the RL problem at differing levels of complexity.\n\nFor more information see [github repository](https://github.com/deepmind/acme).\"\"\"\n\n# Get the version from metadata.\nversion = _metadata.__version__\n\n# If we're releasing a nightly/dev version append to the version string.\nif '--nightly' in sys.argv:\n  sys.argv.remove('--nightly')\n  version += '.dev' + datetime.datetime.now().strftime('%Y%m%d')\n\n\nclass BuildPy(setuptools.command.build_py.build_py):\n\n  def run(self):\n    generate_requirements_file()\n    setuptools.command.build_py.build_py.run(self)\n\n\nclass Develop(setuptools.command.develop.develop):\n\n  def run(self):\n    generate_requirements_file()\n    setuptools.command.develop.develop.run(self)\n\ncmdclass = {\n    'build_py': BuildPy,\n    'develop': Develop,\n}\n\nsetup(\n    name='dm-acme',\n    version=version,\n    cmdclass=cmdclass,\n    description='A Python library for Reinforcement Learning.',\n    long_description=long_description,\n    long_description_content_type='text/markdown',\n    author='DeepMind',\n    license='Apache License, Version 2.0',\n    keywords='reinforcement-learning python machine learning',\n    packages=find_packages(),\n    package_data={'': ['requirements.txt']},\n    include_package_data=True,\n    install_requires=core_requirements,\n    extras_require={\n        'jax': jax_requirements,\n        'tf': tf_requirements,\n        'testing': testing_requirements,\n        'envs': envs_requirements,\n    },\n    classifiers=[\n        'Development Status :: 3 - Alpha',\n        'Environment :: Console',\n        'Intended Audience :: Science/Research',\n        'License :: OSI Approved :: Apache Software License',\n        'Operating System :: POSIX :: Linux',\n        'Programming Language :: Python :: 3',\n        'Programming Language :: Python :: 3.8',\n        'Programming Language :: Python :: 3.9',\n        'Topic :: Scientific/Engineering :: Artificial Intelligence',\n    ],\n)\n","numLines":174,"startLine":1,"totalLines":174}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_d564254192184b29835ee0e1","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t#!/bin/bash\n2\t# Copyright 2018 DeepMind Technologies Limited. All rights reserved.\n3\t#\n4\t# Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the \"License\");\n5\t# you may not use this file except in compliance with the License.\n6\t# You may obtain a copy of the License at\n7\t#\n8\t#     http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0\n9\t#\n10\t# Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software\n11\t# distributed under the License is distributed on an \"AS IS\" BASIS,\n12\t# WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.\n13\t# See the License for the specific language governing permissions and\n14\t# limitations under the License.\n15\t\n16\t\n17\tARGS=()\n18\tDEPS_ONLY=\"\"\n19\t\n20\twhile [[ $# -gt 0 ]]; do\n21\t  case $1 in\n22\t    -d|--deps_only)\n23\t      DEPS_ONLY=1\n24\t      shift\n25\t      ;;\n26\t    *)\n27\t      ARGS+=(\"$1\")\n28\t      shift\n29\t      ;;\n30\t  esac\n31\tdone\n32\t\n33\t# Restore the arguments.\n34\tset -- \"${ARGS[@]}\"\n35\t\n36\t# Bash settings: fail on any error and display all commands being run.\n37\tset -e\n38\tset -x\n39\t\n40\t# Set up a virtual environment.\n41\tpython --version\n42\tpython -m venv acme_testing\n43\tsource acme_testing/bin/activate\n44\t\n45\t# Install dependencies.\n46\tpip install --upgrade pip setuptools wheel xmanager\n47\tpip install .[jax,tf,launchpad,testing,envs]\n48\t\n49\t# Stop early if we only want to install the dependencies.\n50\t[[ -n ${DEPS_ONLY} ]] && exit 0\n51\t\n52\tN_CPU=$(grep -c ^processor /proc/cpuinfo)\n53\tEXAMPLES=$(find examples/ -mindepth 1 -type d -not -path examples/offline -not -path examples/open_spiel -not -path examples/baselines)\n54\t\n55\t# Run static type-checking.\n56\tfor TESTDIR in acme ${EXAMPLES}; do\n57\t  if [`ls *.py | wc -l` != 0]; then\n58\t    pytype -k -j \"${N_CPU}\" \"${TESTDIR}\"\n59\t  fi\n60\tdone\n61\t\n62\t# Run all tests.\n63\tpytest --ignore-glob=\"*/*agent*_test.py\" --durations=10 -n \"${N_CPU}\" acme\n64\t\n65\t# We'll run tests for the continuous baselines.\n66\tcd examples/baselines/rl_continuous\n67\t\n68\t# Run tests for distributed examples.\n69\t# For each of them make sure StepsLimiter reached the limit step count.\n70\tset +x\n71\tset +e\n72\ttime python run_ppo.py --run_distributed=True --lp_termination_notice_secs=1 \\\n73\t  --env_name=gym:MountainCarContinuous-v0 --num_steps=1000 \\\n74\t  --num_distributed_actors=4 > /tmp/log.txt 2>&1\n75\tset -x\n76\tset -e\n77\tcat /tmp/log.txt\n78\tcat /tmp/log.txt | grep -E 'StepsLimiter: Max steps of [0-9]+ was reached, terminating'\n79\t\n80\t# Run tests for non-distributed examples.\n81\tTEST_COUNT=0\n82\tfor TEST in run_*.py; do\n83\t  echo \"TEST: ${TEST}\"\n84\t  TEST_COUNT=$(($TEST_COUNT+1))\n85\t  if [ $TEST == 'run_dmpo.py' ] ||\n86\t     [ $TEST == 'run_mogmpo.py' ] ||\n87\t     [ $TEST == 'run_mpo.py' ]; then\n88\t    # This is a known breakage at the moment.\n89\t    continue;\n90\t  fi\n91\t  time python \"${TEST}\" --run_distributed=False --num_steps=1000 \\\n92\t    --eval_every=1000 --env_name=gym:MountainCarContinuous-v0\n93\t\n94\tdone\n95\t# Make sure number of executed examples is expected. This makes sure\n96\t# we will not forget to update this code when examples are renamed for example.\n97\tif [ $TEST_COUNT -ne 7 ]; then\n98\t  exit 1\n99\tfi\n100\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"db66edc6-7466-48f8-a0c7-bcc0b007df7f","uuid":"9a3104de-422a-412d-ba37-6e1af6cb9071","timestamp":"2026-04-06T16:59:17.734Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/test.sh","content":"#!/bin/bash\n# Copyright 2018 DeepMind Technologies Limited. All rights reserved.\n#\n# Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the \"License\");\n# you may not use this file except in compliance with the License.\n# You may obtain a copy of the License at\n#\n#     http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0\n#\n# Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software\n# distributed under the License is distributed on an \"AS IS\" BASIS,\n# WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.\n# See the License for the specific language governing permissions and\n# limitations under the License.\n\n\nARGS=()\nDEPS_ONLY=\"\"\n\nwhile [[ $# -gt 0 ]]; do\n  case $1 in\n    -d|--deps_only)\n      DEPS_ONLY=1\n      shift\n      ;;\n    *)\n      ARGS+=(\"$1\")\n      shift\n      ;;\n  esac\ndone\n\n# Restore the arguments.\nset -- \"${ARGS[@]}\"\n\n# Bash settings: fail on any error and display all commands being run.\nset -e\nset -x\n\n# Set up a virtual environment.\npython --version\npython -m venv acme_testing\nsource acme_testing/bin/activate\n\n# Install dependencies.\npip install --upgrade pip setuptools wheel xmanager\npip install .[jax,tf,launchpad,testing,envs]\n\n# Stop early if we only want to install the dependencies.\n[[ -n ${DEPS_ONLY} ]] && exit 0\n\nN_CPU=$(grep -c ^processor /proc/cpuinfo)\nEXAMPLES=$(find examples/ -mindepth 1 -type d -not -path examples/offline -not -path examples/open_spiel -not -path examples/baselines)\n\n# Run static type-checking.\nfor TESTDIR in acme ${EXAMPLES}; do\n  if [`ls *.py | wc -l` != 0]; then\n    pytype -k -j \"${N_CPU}\" \"${TESTDIR}\"\n  fi\ndone\n\n# Run all tests.\npytest --ignore-glob=\"*/*agent*_test.py\" --durations=10 -n \"${N_CPU}\" acme\n\n# We'll run tests for the continuous baselines.\ncd examples/baselines/rl_continuous\n\n# Run tests for distributed examples.\n# For each of them make sure StepsLimiter reached the limit step count.\nset +x\nset +e\ntime python run_ppo.py --run_distributed=True --lp_termination_notice_secs=1 \\\n  --env_name=gym:MountainCarContinuous-v0 --num_steps=1000 \\\n  --num_distributed_actors=4 > /tmp/log.txt 2>&1\nset -x\nset -e\ncat /tmp/log.txt\ncat /tmp/log.txt | grep -E 'StepsLimiter: Max steps of [0-9]+ was reached, terminating'\n\n# Run tests for non-distributed examples.\nTEST_COUNT=0\nfor TEST in run_*.py; do\n  echo \"TEST: ${TEST}\"\n  TEST_COUNT=$(($TEST_COUNT+1))\n  if [ $TEST == 'run_dmpo.py' ] ||\n     [ $TEST == 'run_mogmpo.py' ] ||\n     [ $TEST == 'run_mpo.py' ]; then\n    # This is a known breakage at the moment.\n    continue;\n  fi\n  time python \"${TEST}\" --run_distributed=False --num_steps=1000 \\\n    --eval_every=1000 --env_name=gym:MountainCarContinuous-v0\n\ndone\n# Make sure number of executed examples is expected. This makes sure\n# we will not forget to update this code when examples are renamed for example.\nif [ $TEST_COUNT -ne 7 ]; then\n  exit 1\nfi\n","numLines":100,"startLine":1,"totalLines":100}}}
